{
  "doc_id": "5210",
  "text": "CD94 is primarily associated with the NKG2A isoform, forming an inhibitory receptor, but can also be complexed with NKG2C/E, forming activating receptors [CITATION_1] . Ligation of Qa-1/ Qdm with CD94/NKG2A results in inhibition of NK cell cytolytic activity [CITATION_2] . As the presentation of Qdm and other leader sequence peptides is dependent on transporter associated with antigen processing (TAP), the absence of HLA-E/Qa-1 bound to the endogenous peptides allows NK cells to detect and lyse abnormal cells [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . CD8 + T cell responses to viral infection can also be dampened through the interaction of Qa-1/Qdm with CD94/NKG2A [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . Lastly, Qa-1 is the restriction element for a subset of suppressor CD8 + T cells, called",
